    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-11-09T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-11-09T05:00:00-05:00" n="298"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d298">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.018/11–948: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-11-09T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 9, 1948—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 9—7:56 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2358. Following excerpts from November 7 <hi rend="italic">Tribune</hi> (MOI<note
                        n="1" xml:id="d298fn1">Ministry of Information.</note>) editorial on
                        Badger’s<note n="2" xml:id="d298fn2">Adm. Oscar C. Badger, Commander, U. S.
                        Naval Forces, Western Pacific (ComNavWesPac).</note> remarks re use Marines
                    in Shanghai is typical straw-grasping thinking now prevalent there: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“But there seems no reason why the Chinese Government should not, if the
                            occasion arise, seek the cooperation of American Navy and Marines in
                            preservation of law and order in this great city—one of world’s
                            largest—where so many international interests are represented. It might
                            be well perhaps if Shanghai could be considered ‘open city’ and free
                            from anxieties of war until such time as agreed arrangements could be
                            made for its future role in Chinese economy.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department 2358, repeated Nanking 1786.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
